Haven’t done one of these in a while.

The Sierra Nevada red fox (Vulpes vulpes necator) is a rare subspecies of red fox native to California. It is considered one of the most endangered animals in North America, with an estimated population of less than 50 individuals. Estimations have varied, as an accurate count of the species is difficult to perform because of how rare they are, but some have been as low as 15 individuals. An explanation on why they are so threatened is unknown, but the most common reasonings are disease, competition with coyotes, and destruction of habitat.

They live in the mountain ranges of California, but have since expanded to Oregon and Nevada. They used to inhabit a vast stretch of the mountains, however many populations have gone extinct locally. It was even thought that they had gone extinct in the Sierra Nevada up until 2010, when one was sighted for the first time in the area in 19 years. Studying them is difficult, as they are solitary animals living in remote habitats, in addition to their crepuscular lifestyle and general avoidance of humans. Although like most foxes, a few have been known to scavenge from human settlements.
